sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1830017
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is the main construct cloned by the iGEM Concordia 2015 team. It is the entire DNA sequence that allows for the Induction, expression, targeting and attachment of an extracellular scaffold onto the extracellular membrane of the lactic acid bacteria ''Lactococcus Lactis''. This scaffold contains two different dockerin domain that allow for the specific harboring of cohesin-fused proteins.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Mathieu Husser
